                                          text: "<p>A publication reports the outcome of a new statin therapy in a placebo controlled primary prevention of ischaemic heart disease in a diabetic population.</p>  <p>1000 patients were randomised to receive the new therapy and 1000 allocated to placebo. The study was completed over a five year period.</p>  <p>In the placebo group there were 150 myocardial infarcts (MI) and in the group treated with the new statin there were 100 myocardial infarcts.</p>  <p>What is the number needed to treat to prevent one MI over the course of this study?</p>",
                                          comment: "<p>You treat 1000 patients for five years with the new statin and prevent 50 MIs.</p>  <p>Thus the number needed to treat (NNT) to prevent one MI is 20 (1000/50).</p>  <p>This statistical figure provides us with a lot of information regarding the efficacy of a treatment rather than purely statistically significant data.</p>  <p>As it stands, you may expect to prevent an infarct by treating as few as 20 patients over five years from these data.</p>  <p>Furthermore, cost economic data can be calculated from such results by factoring in how much the drug costs against all the costs of treating and rehabilitating a patient with an MI.</p>",
